Ever heard of covert incest? 

Silently seduced: when parents make their children partners, by Kenneth M. 
Adams

When he's married to mom: how to help mother-enmeshed men open their hearts 
to true love and commitment, by Kenneth M. Adams

There are different types and intensities of abuse (emmotional, physical, 
sexual) but the bottom line is the same: the abuse is subconscious. The 
victim (the child) feels discomfort, anger, resentment, but at the same 
time feels guilt which binds him to the abusive figure and prevents 
him(/her) from detaching as it would mean "death" to the dependent child.
This process begins at a very early age and continues until the victim 
becomes aware of it (by calling it up from the unconscious).
The victim, let's say a son, is being, let's say emotionally abused (covert 
incest) by his mother. The son is aware of this on his unconscious level. 
The son can't do to anything about it, because he is binded by shame. But 
the anger and resent begin to pile up. The son doesn't consciously 
recognize the mother as the source of manipulation, neither can he take it 
out on her - because she is his "mother". So, he takes these feelings of 
hate and resentment and projects them onto other female figures.
The worse the manipulation and the abuse are, the harder it is for the ego 
to take. Once the boundries of the ego are crossed, violent outbursts start 
to take place.

In my opinion, Elliot was a victim of systematic abuse from the mother, 
from the grandmothers, abandoned by his "abscent" father and thus sexually 
frustrated, angry and resentful, acted-out on the environment, 
externalizing the conflict that was within.

Now, there are no "evil" people in this story. Even the abusers were once 
the abused. This is a subconscious patern that fuels a viscious circle. And 
it only get's broken, once a victim becomes aware of the true problem and 
resolves it through insight, ussually with the help of a psychotherapyst.
I also claim, that problems in society are a consequence of such 
individuals. Solve the problems in the primary familly relations and you 
will consequently get a better society.﻿

All the people hating on Elliot Rodger -- instead of hating the guy 
understand his life and learn from it -- your hatred of him blinds your 
ability to learn valuable lessons. Obviously what he did was horrific and 
he should be condemned, but he had a lot of psychological issues that we 
can learn from, and a lot of twisted points of view that we can examine in 
order to learn more about our culture. I hate to admit it but reading some 
of his manifesto I could relate to feelings of alienation, anger, etc at 
being passed over -- a lot of men in our culutre feel entitled == I beileve 
this is a problem with men but also points to misoginistic points of view 
and a sexually repsressed culture in which men who dont get a lot of sex 
feel a whole shit ton of FOMO -- Ive certainly felt lovely and alienated a 
lot of my life, I dont resent women for it though -- I can put it in 
context and come to terms with it -- a lot of rodgers' beliefs were built 
up over years.

I think we live in a violent culture that leads many to feel a deep inner 
pain and alienation -- I could go on and on === but my main point is that 
no man is an island -- it's easy enough to call the kid crazy without 
taking a close look at all the elements -- his parents, his friends, and 
his manifesto -- anyone who hates on him without a proper examination is a 
fool and deserves to learn as little from this tregedy as they belie in 
their comments.﻿

Here many of us here see our right to firearms differently. We feel that 
our 2nd Amendment (right to bear arms shall not be infringed) doesn't GIVE 
us the right to have our guns; what it does is (in theory, anyway) prevent 
government from infringing on those rights, which we see as a natural right 
of the people.

For us, it's not about hunting. It's about our Constitution, which prevents 
abuses of governmental power. We believe in a system of "checks and 
balances" within our government, which also aids in the prevention of 
abuses on the people. Part of this includes the right of the people to bear 
arms: not only for personal defense and hunting but so that we should be 
capable of rising up and putting an end to tyranny in America should it 
ever occur. The 2nd Amendment is often viewed as the "teeth" in our 
Constitution. In other words, it's the one that will actually enable us to 
do something about it when the rest of our Constitution is no longer 
honored or respected by those acting like our masters.

Don't think that it's lost on us that Hitler was elected into power in a 
democratic environment before disarming, torturing, and killing the Jews in 
mass quantity. This is EXACTLY the kind of thing our Bill of Rights aims to 
prevent.

Will we have an occasional mass shooting? Yes, we will and we do, 
unfortunately. It's horrible--no one can deny that. Everything in life is 
give and take though; and the very laws that enable the occasional misfit 
to go on a shooting rampage also prevent a Hitler from rising to power here 
in America (as well give us the ability to defend ourselves).

And with the way our government has been behaving: waging wars of 
aggression based on lies they made to the public, the illegal NSA spying, 
and writing laws enabling them to detain American citizens indefinitely 
without access to a lawyer or due process, Americans are becoming less 
trustful of the government as it seems the possibility exists that tyranny 
isn't that far off here in America. For these reasons, we'd like our 
Constitution to keep it's 'teeth.'

Also, if you look at the data, most gun related deaths in America are also 
done by criminal gangs with illegal guns obtained on the black market. 
These people are not an accurate reflection of Americans in general, nor 
does their culture of death and drugs accurately represent our culture.

Freedom is truly is what our culture is all about, and firearms ownership 
is how we maintain that freedom.
